<div
  data-particle_enable="false"
  data-particle-mobile-disabled="false"
  class="elementor-element elementor-element-fb713a0 e-con-full e-flex e-con e-child"
  data-id="fb713a0"
  data-element_type="container"
>
  <div
    class="elementor-element elementor-element-b8ac37f elementor-hidden-mobile elementor-widget elementor-widget-heading"
    data-id="b8ac37f"
    data-element_type="widget"
    data-widget_type="heading.default"
  >
    <div class="elementor-widget-container">
      <h2 class="elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default">
        Military Service &amp; Veterans&nbsp;REQUIREMENTS
      </h2>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div
    class="elementor-element elementor-element-e7db502 elementor-hidden-desktop elementor-hidden-tablet elementor-widget elementor-widget-heading"
    data-id="e7db502"
    data-element_type="widget"
    data-widget_type="heading.default"
  >
    <div class="elementor-widget-container">
      <h2 class="elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default">
        Military Service &amp; Veterans<br />REQUIREMENTS
      </h2>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div
    class="elementor-element elementor-element-c9f3288 elementor-widget elementor-widget-text-editor"
    data-id="c9f3288"
    data-element_type="widget"
    data-widget_type="text-editor.default"
  >
    <div class="elementor-widget-container">
      <p><strong>1. Explore Military Heritage. </strong>Do the following:</p>
      <ul style="list-style-type: none">
        <li>
          (a) Learn about Robert Baden-Powell’s military service. Discuss with
          your counselor what he learned about people, values, and culture
          through his military service and how it influenced the founding of
          Scouting. <br /><strong
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8xW61FgOImw"
              >Robert Baden Powell (6 Min) (video)</a
            ></strong
          ><br /><strong
            ><a
              href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Robert-Stephenson-Smyth-Baden-Powell-1st-Baron-Baden-Powell"
              >Robert Baden-Powell (website) [Britannica]</a
            ></strong
          >
        </li>
        <li>
          (b) Select a historical military conflict. Discuss with your counselor
          what caused it and how leadership, planning, or values affected its
          outcome, how it was resolved, and discuss what lessons can be learned
          from it. <br /><strong
            ><u>American Revolution<br /></u
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NdRuU5ON-LU"
              >American Revolutionary War – Timelines and Maps – Animated US
              History (9 Min) (video)</a
            ><u><br /></u
            ><a
              href="https://www.loc.gov/classroom-materials/united-states-history-primary-source-timeline/american-revolution-1763-1783/overview/"
              >History of the American Revolution (Website) [Library of
              Congress]</a
            ></strong
          ><u
            ><br /><strong>Civil War<br /></strong></u
          ><strong
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=T3ryzrowNKc"
              >The American Civil War Explained (3 Min) (video)</a
            ><u><br /></u
            ><a
              href="https://www.loc.gov/classroom-materials/united-states-history-primary-source-timeline/civil-war-and-reconstruction-1861-1877/overview/"
              >History of the US Civil War (website) [Library of Congress]
            </a></strong
          ><u
            ><br /><strong>World War I<br /></strong></u
          ><strong
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c7nUDLKKEBY"
              >How Did WW I Start? (9 Min) (video)</a
            ><u><br /></u
            ><a
              href="https://www.loc.gov/classroom-materials/united-states-history-primary-source-timeline/progressive-era-to-new-era-1900-1929/united-states-participation-in-world-war-i/"
              >U.S. Participation in World War I (website) [Library of
              Congress]</a
            ></strong
          ><u
            ><br /><strong>World War II<br /></strong></u
          ><strong
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGlRJKsRozA"
              >World War II – Explained (5 Min) (video)</a
            ><u><br /></u
            ><a
              href="https://www.loc.gov/classroom-materials/united-states-history-primary-source-timeline/great-depression-and-world-war-ii-1929-1945/world-war-ii/"
              >World War II (website) [Library of Congress]</a
            ></strong
          ><u
            ><br /><strong>Korean War<br /></strong></u
          ><strong
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h1wFrXKanC0"
              >The Korean War: 5 Things to Know (4 Min) (video)</a
            ><u><br /></u
            ><a
              href="https://spice.fsi.stanford.edu/docs/overview_of_the__korean_war_and_its_legacy"
              >Korea War Overview (website) [Stanford University]</a
            ></strong
          ><u
            ><br /><strong>Vietnam War<br /></strong></u
          ><strong
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XD08SZxKU2Y"
              >Vietnam War explained&nbsp; (3 Min) (video)</a
            ><u><br /></u
            ><a
              href="https://www.vassar.edu/the-wars-for-vietnam/vietnam-war-overview"
              >Vietnam War Overview (website) [Vassar]</a
            ></strong
          ><u
            ><br /><strong>Gulf War<br /></strong></u
          ><strong
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xl_lctDXHuQ"
              >What Happened in the Persian Gulf War? (4 Min) (video)</a
            ><u><br /></u
            ><a href="https://www.history.com/articles/persian-gulf-war"
              >Gulf War Overview (website) [History.com]</a
            ></strong
          >
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>&nbsp;</p>
      <p>
        <strong>2. Understand the Cost of War and the Value of Peace. </strong
        >Do the following:
      </p>
      <ul style="list-style-type: none">
        <li>
          (a) Discuss with your counselor why military conflict should be a last
          resort.
        </li>
        <li>(b) Do ONE of the following:&nbsp;</li>
      </ul>
      <ol>
        <li style="list-style-type: none">
          <ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha">
            <li>
              Read or listen to President Dwight D. Eisenhower’s “Atoms for
              Peace” speech and explain the objectives and role of the
              International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) in promoting peaceful
              uses of nuclear energy. <br /><strong
                ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2DxeLeginUQ"
                  >Atoms For Peace Speech Eisenhower (11 Min) (video)</a
                ></strong
              ><br /><strong
                ><a
                  href="https://www.eisenhowerlibrary.gov/research/online-documents/atoms-peace"
                  >Atoms for Peace Overview (website) [Eisenhower Library]
                </a></strong
              ><br /><strong
                ><a href="http://www.iaea.org/"
                  >International Atomic Energy Agency (website) [IAEA]
                </a></strong
              >
            </li>
          </ol>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha">
        <li style="list-style-type: none">
          <ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha" start="2">
            <li>
              Explain the role of the United Nations in promoting peace and
              resolving international disputes.<br /><strong
                ><a href="https://peacekeeping.un.org/en"
                  >United Nations Peacekeeping (website)</a
                ></strong
              >
            </li>
          </ol>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p>&nbsp;</p>
      <ul style="list-style-type: none">
        <li>
          (c) Reflect on the human and societal costs of war and share the
          lessons that can be learned from major conflicts.<br /><strong
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bi_dbJBqNUA"
              >The Impact of War on Civilians: Understanding the Human Cost of
              Conflict (2.5 Min) (video)
            </a></strong
          >
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>&nbsp;</p>
      <p>
        <strong>3. United States Armed Forces. </strong>Do ONE of the following:
      </p>
      <ul style="list-style-type: none">
        <li>
          (a) Choose one of the branches of service of the United States and
          research its history, its mission, and its organization. Explain to
          your counselor what you learned.<br /><strong
            ><u>US Air Force<br /></u
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jm0DCIS38T0"
              >The EPIC History of the U.S. Air Force (4.5 Min) (video)</a
            ><u><br /></u
            ><a
              href="https://www.clemson.edu/business/academics/air-rotc/about/history.html"
              >History of the US Air Force (website) [Clemson University]</a
            ></strong
          ><u><br /></u><strong><u>US Army</u></strong
          ><br /><strong
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z4DmoTrRVw0"
              >Center of Military History (5 Min) (video)</a
            ><u><br /></u
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0pOjfwL3gpA"
              >US Army Structure EXPLAINED! (4 Min) (video)</a
            ><u><br /></u
            ><a href="https://www.legendsofamerica.com/army-history-timeline/"
              >History of the US Army (website)</a
            ></strong
          ><u><br /></u
          ><strong
            ><u>US Coast Guard<br /></u
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CTib37o8TGU"
              >United States Coast Guard – 1790 to Today – A Short History (4
              Min) (video)</a
            ><u><br /></u
            ><a
              href="https://thegracemuseum.org/learn/2020-6-10-history-of-the-us-coast-guard/"
              >History of the US Coast Guard (website) [The Grace]</a
            ></strong
          ><u><br /></u
          ><strong
            ><u>US Marine Corps<br /></u
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j9yef9Zxgww"
              >Short History of the Marines (4.5 Min) (video)</a
            ><u><br /></u
            ><a
              href="https://www.ebsco.com/research-starters/history/united-states-marine-corps"
              >Summarized History of the USMC&nbsp; (website)</a
            ></strong
          ><u><br /></u><strong><u>US Navy</u></strong
          ><strong
            ><br /><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6-2Kac2xSZ0"
              >The History of the United States Navy (6 Min) (video)</a
            ></strong
          ><br /><strong
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Gan3GQnPQf4"
              >Every US Navy Fleet Explained (9 Min) (video)</a
            ><u><br /></u
            ><a
              href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/United-States-Navy/Theories-of-force-projection-and-World-War-I"
              >History of the United States Navy (website) [Britannica]</a
            ></strong
          ><u><br /></u
          ><strong
            ><u>US Space Force<br /></u
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=66V_wcePi6k"
              >Exploring the United States Space Force: History, Mission, and
              Capabilities (6 Min) (video)</a
            ><u><br /></u
            ><a href="https://www.britannica.com/science/space-exploration"
              >Britannica Space Force Article (website)</a
            ></strong
          >
        </li>
        <li>
          (b) Learn about the Veterans History Project organized by the Library
          of Congress. Conduct and record an interview of a veteran using those
          guidelines. Share your recording with your counselor and the veteran.
          With the veteran’s permission, share it with the Library of
          Congress.<br /><strong
            ><a
              href="https://www.loc.gov/programs/veterans-history-project/how-to-participate/customized-guidance/"
              >Youth Participation and Guidelines (website)</a
            ></strong
          ><br /><strong
            ><a
              href="https://www.loc.gov/static/programs/veterans-history-project/documents/for-scouts-custom-guidance.pdf"
              >Customized Guidance for Scouts (PDF)
            </a></strong
          ><br /><strong
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y-zMq13vKiY"
              >Library of Congress Project Aims to Save Veterans’ Stories (2.5
              Min) (video)</a
            ></strong
          >
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>&nbsp;</p>
      <p>
        <strong>4. Understand Military Recognition. </strong>Do the following:
      </p>
      <ul style="list-style-type: none">
        <li>
          (a) Explain the history and significance of the Medal of Honor and the
          Purple Heart.<br /><strong
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3ZwXgTnH854"
              >In Their Own Words: An Introduction to the Medal of Honor and Its
              Recipients (10 Min) (video)</a
            ></strong
          ><br /><strong
            ><a href="https://www.cem.va.gov/history/Medal-of-Honor-history.asp"
              >Medal of Honor History &amp; Recipients (website) [Veteran
              Affairs]</a
            ></strong
          ><br /><strong
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/shorts/Tv8Om9utYXs"
              >The Purple Heart (1 Min) (video)</a
            ></strong
          ><br /><strong
            ><a
              href="https://www.nationalww2museum.org/war/articles/history-of-the-purple-heart"
              >The History of the Purple Heart (Website) [National WWII
              Museum]</a
            ></strong
          >
        </li>
        <li>
          (b) Describe the qualifications for receiving each award.
          <br /><strong
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZxhI7JvyXlk"
              >The INTENSE Process of Awarding a Medal of Honor: Step by Step (5
              Min) (video)</a
            ></strong
          ><br /><strong
            ><a
              href="https://www.cmohs.org/news-events/blog/how-is-the-medal-of-honor-awarded/"
              >How is the Medal of Honor Awarded? (website) [Medal of Honor
              Foundation]</a
            ></strong
          ><br /><strong
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OcCch7iMRAM"
              >What Is the Criteria for Receiving a Purple Heart?(3.5 Min)
              (video)</a
            ><br /><a
              href="https://crawfordcountyveteransohio.com/blog/purple-heart-qualifications-guidance/"
              >Understanding Purple Heart Qualifications (website)</a
            ></strong
          >
        </li>
        <li>
          (c) Research a Medal of Honor recipient and share their story with
          your counselor. Explain why their actions were recognized.<br /><strong
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M_t1_fzFSOI"
              >Famous American Medal of Honor Recipients (13 Min) (video)</a
            ></strong
          ><br /><strong
            ><a href="https://www.cmohs.org/recipients"
              >Medal of Honor Recipients (website) [Congressional Medal of Honor
              Society]</a
            ></strong
          >
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        <br /><strong>5. Military Uniforms and Insignia.</strong> Do the
        following:
      </p>
      <ul style="list-style-type: none">
        <li>
          (a) Learn about the purpose and history of military uniforms and
          insignia. <br /><strong
            ><a href="https://www.war.gov/Resources/Insignias/#officer-insignia"
              >https://www.war.gov/Resources/Insignias/#officer-insignia</a
            ></strong
          ><br /><strong
            ><a
              href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uniforms_of_the_United_States_Armed_Forces"
              >https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uniforms_of_the_United_States_Armed_Forces</a
            ></strong
          >
        </li>
        <li>
          (b) Identify the different uniforms worn by members of the U.S. Army,
          Navy, Marine Corps, Air&nbsp; Force, Space Force, and Coast Guard.
        </li>
        <li>
          (c) Learn to identify and describe the rank insignia for all enlisted
          and officer ranks from one branch of the U.S. Armed Forces. <br /><a
            href="https://veteran.com/military-ranks-insignia-charts/"
            ><strong
              >U.S. Military Ranks &amp; Pay Grade by Branch (website)
              [Veterans.com]</strong
            ></a
          >
        </li>
        <li>
          (d) Explain how rank and insignia show respect, order, and
          responsibility within the military.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        <br /><strong>6. Reflect on Symbols of Service. </strong>Do the
        following:
      </p>
      <ul style="list-style-type: none">
        <li>
          (a) Discuss with an active-duty member, reservist, or veteran what
          their uniform and the American Flag mean to them as a military member.
          Share what you learned with your counselor. Describe what proper
          respect for the flag means to them.
        </li>
        <li>
          (b) Discuss with your counselor what your uniform and troop flag mean
          to you.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>&nbsp;</p>
      <p><strong>7. Honor Veterans. </strong>Do the following:</p>
      <ul style="list-style-type: none">
        <li>
          (a) Participate in a Veterans Day, Memorial Day, or other event that
          honors veterans in your community, school, or place of worship.
          <br /><strong
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mWD4Oy6fKlo&amp;t=2s"
              >Bet You Didn’t Know: Veterans Day | History (2 Min) (video)</a
            ></strong
          ><br /><a
            href="https://department.va.gov/veterans-day/history-of-veterans-day/"
            ><strong
              >History of Veterans Day (website) [Veterans Affairs]</strong
            ></a
          >
        </li>
        <li>
          (b) Discuss with your counselor what role you played and what you
          learned from the experience.
        </li>
        <li>
          (c) Visit a veterans’ organization, military museum, memorial, or
          cemetery. Discuss with your counselor what you learned about service,
          sacrifice, and remembrance.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p><br /><strong>8. Military Academies. </strong>Do the following:</p>
      <ul style="list-style-type: none">
        <li>
          (a) Learn about the purpose and history of TWO of the U.S. military
          academies: the U.S. Military Academy at West Point, the U.S. Naval
          Academy, the U.S. Air Force Academy, the U.S. Coast&nbsp; Guard
          Academy, and the U.S. Merchant Marine Academy.<br /><a
            href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-Puh39QSVRI"
            ><strong
              >All US Military Academies Explained (7 Min) (video)</strong
            ></a
          >
        </li>
        <li>
          (b) Explain the general requirements for admission to one of these
          academies. <br /><a
            href="https://www.collegeessayguy.com/blog/us-military-service-academies-guide"
            ><strong
              >A Guide to the US Military Service Academies (website)</strong
            ></a
          >
        </li>
        <li>
          (c) Describe how attending a service academy prepares a person for
          military leadership and service to the nation.
        </li>
        <li>
          (d) Discuss with your counselor how the values of Scouting align with
          those of the military academies.<br /><a href="https://westpoint.edu"
            ><strong>https://westpoint.edu</strong></a
          ><br /><a href="https://www.usna.edu/homepage.php"
            ><strong>https://www.usna.edu/homepage.php </strong></a
          ><br /><a href="https://www.usafa.edu"
            ><strong>https://www.usafa.edu </strong></a
          ><br /><a href="https://uscga.edu"
            ><strong>https://uscga.edu </strong></a
          ><br /><a href="https://www.usmma.edu"
            ><strong>https://www.usmma.edu</strong></a
          ><u><br /><br /></u>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        <strong>9. Inspire Service and Leadership. </strong>Do the following:
      </p>
      <ul style="list-style-type: none">
        <li>
          (a) Discuss how learning about veterans and military service can
          inspire youth to serve their community and country. <br /><strong
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZffcUB1ZlxM"
              >Scoutmaster Talks About How Military Life Affects Scouting (2.5
              Min)</a
            ><br /><a
              href="https://ucnet.universityofcalifornia.edu/wp-content/uploads/working-at-uc/your-career/veterans/_files/21_Strengths_Arising_From_Military_Experience.pdf"
              >21 Strengths Arising From Military Experience (PDF)</a
            ></strong
          >
        </li>
        <li>
          (b) List two ways you can demonstrate courage, service, or leadership
          in your daily life.<br /><strong
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-fku1Evr7Vo"
              >The BEST Place to Find Courage (2 Min) (video)</a
            ></strong
          ><br /><a
            href="https://www.colorado.edu/orientation/2024/02/29/6-ways-students-can-demonstrate-leadership"
            ><strong
              >6 Ways Students can Demonstrate Leadership (website) [University
              of Colorado]</strong
            ></a
          >
        </li>
        <li>
          (c) Research service projects in your area that honor veterans or
          support those currently serving. Share what you learned with your
          counselor.<br /><strong
            ><a href="https://www.youtube.com/shorts/FFRlU2fl0nc"
              >Honoring Heroes: 10 Eagle Scout Projects Dedicated to Veterans (1
              min) (video)</a
            ></strong
          ><br /><a
            href="https://elks.org/SharedElksOrg/enf/files/TwentyProjectIdeasforServingVeterans.pdf"
            ><strong>20 Project Ideas for Serving Veterans (PDF)</strong></a
          >
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>&nbsp;</p>
      <p>
        <strong>10. Careers. </strong>Explore careers related to this military
        service. Research one career to learn about the training and education
        needed, costs, job prospects, salary, job duties, and career
        advancement. Your research methods may include — with your parent or
        guardian’s permission — an internet or library search, an interview with
        a professional in the field, or a visit to a location where people in
        this career work. Discuss with your counselor both your findings and
        what about this profession might make it an interesting career.
      </p>
      <ul style="list-style-type: none">
        <li>
          <strong
            ><a href="https://youtu.be/LbNP0FUItjI?si=ldSxlAsuMOHw9JsA"
              >U.S. Air Force – Own the Sky</a
            ><br /></strong
          ><strong
            ><a href="https://youtu.be/luc9saxt_YQ?si=ta-_QOTrZeoW_HF4"
              >First Jump | Be All You Can Be | U.S. Army</a
            ><br /></strong
          ><strong
            ><a href="https://youtu.be/_CfGZ_TvTeI?si=ASAIOSsOIspLd9CT"
              >Coast Guard – What Makes a Life?</a
            ><br /></strong
          ><strong
            ><a href="https://youtu.be/L2ljqUpkC1c"
              >My Why | U.S. Marine Corps</a
            ><br /></strong
          ><a href="https://youtu.be/b_FL2yiCJSE?si=bRzZSvPec2qhy3MZ"
            ><strong>Strong Enough – US Navy</strong></a
          ><br /><a href="https://youtu.be/R9bzFKHrQoo?si=U_qkxxjK66zMCAXl"
            ><strong>U.S. Space Force – Origins</strong></a
          >
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
